The Prague Stock Exchange fell into a negative at the end of trading
After a sharp fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected the losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares have reached almost half of the normal daily trade.
The Prague Stock Exchange resumed its decline on Monday from the beginning of Tuesday, when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, the decline in stocks on Wall Street is behind the decline.
This is also how the market reacts to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the plan of stabilization of the local financial sector.
Falling Stocks in Asia
The Asian stock market experienced a dramatic decline on Tuesday, although the indices eventually wiped out some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng stock exchange in Hong Kong wrote off almost four percent during trading, but later deleted some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8%, while the markets in Shanghai were closed.
Stocks on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually fell to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent according to the index.
“The timing of the U.S. bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy independently, i.e. without dependence on the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should quickly return to negotiations and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, they say, other countries will also be affected.
The Bloodbath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which was to spend up to $700 billion (nearly CZK 12 trillion).
Legislators have thus ignored President George W. Bush’s call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks suffered a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices saw their biggest fall in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell by almost seven percent and last saw a similar decline in 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the proposal did not pass in the House, the index found itself in a free fall.
Congress backs down: U.S. government could pump $700 billion into banks
U.S. Congressional leaders and President George W. Bush’s government have agreed on a broader financial aid deal for the U.S. financial system.
Voting on it will be early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in talks to approve a rescue plan in the form of financial aid to the U.S. financial system worth $700 billion (approximately 12 trillion crowns).
However, it has not yet been won.
Congressmen must complete some details of the agreement before they can publish the final form of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed at the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Services Committee, told Reuters.
According to sources, the plan could be voted on in the Senate first Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first significant psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
Then, however, there will be "sobering up" thanks to the complexity of the mechanisms by which to help markets achieve in practice.
Paulson: Plan needs to be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differences of opinion on what the market stabilisation package should look like,” Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, told Bloomberg.
According to him, the final vote could take place on Sunday.
On Sunday, lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to give a definitive look to the government fund.
He should buy back unsold mortgage assets from financial companies, which pull financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
We need to continue the recovery plan, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
Signal for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to calm investors before trading on the Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone where Congress’ decision could affect Monday’s trading.
However, it is not yet clear when the two chambers of the US Congress will vote on the bill, or whether the last-minute negotiations could tie in with a problem.
Legislators hope it will be approved in the next few days.
However, the law still makes a number of changes.
The total amount earmarked for aid to the scheme is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is expected to be made available as soon as possible, as President George W. Bush has demanded.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it has the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, in a succession of another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush Appreciates Progress in Negotiations
The president can veto the decision, but Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to raise funds for the purchase of bad mortgage securities, the value of which has collapsed because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, remained.
“We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday,” said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
U.S. President Bush is also pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was satisfied with Saturday’s progress and praised “the two-way effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Restrictions on gold parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, a senior negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on accountability for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing reliefs, and timing of funding for the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establish a committee to supervise the fund.
It should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on this and made great progress towards a deal that will work and will be useful for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes assistance for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new installments on the mortgages it buys, in order to reduce monthly repayment costs for debtors and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to chief economist Patrio Finance David Marko, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement it.
"This is because it is not known by what mechanism and at what price the problem assets will be redeemed.
This will be decisive for how the financial sector and the government share their losses,” Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not that important, according to Mark.
“It is much more important that this week’s congressmen agree that they support this plan and that they will consecrate it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement to be approved is the most important at the moment,” Marek said.
Knife Blade Fight: MP3 Players vs Mobiles.
We will advise you how to choose
While almost every cell phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
I think it’s better to just buy a phone.
However, there are plenty of reasons to buy a separate player.
The choice completely depends on the method of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It’s hard to get a top-of-the-line, expensive turntable at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
On the one hand, such music products do not appear on LPs and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
However, if there are vinyls with art rock, jazz or blues in your shelves, you probably at least dream of such a turntable.
The same is true of music on the go, that is, music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a player, as well as a fan of Pink Floyd, it may be difficult to try the headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
The battery life also depends.
Some high-end music players can do much more than just play music, but what most mobiles do by no means.
No current device is as versatile as a phone.
In addition to its primary functions, phone calls and texting, it can play music and video, record both, have a better, a worse camera, and maybe even navigate.
And if we take smartphones and communicators into account, you will also have a small computer in your pocket.
It’s a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can photograph anything.
The versatility of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more features you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator on the display sends you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
Therefore, for cheap mobile phones, count on the fact that you will not play for more than a few hours.
If you call here and there, get another charger to work for sure - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you will not have this problem, even the worst ones will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem arises when recording music to a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but few card readers can cope with the miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without any reduction.
With the exception of iPods, you don’t need any special software.
Just fill your device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players create their own music library, sorted by the artist’s name, album name, genre or user rating.
Some devices display only the directory tree structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, operating system smartphones).
Players are easier to use, mobiles can do more
When choosing a specific device, be especially interested in battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output and, of course, comfort of operation.
If music is primarily a backdrop for you and if you listen to it every day for a short time, for example, on the tram, you need any phone that plays MP3.
This can be done by almost any mobile phone.
You don’t even have to watch too much what music formats your phone or player can do.
MP3s can handle everything, and the vast majority of music that gets to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most common and besides it, the vast majority of devices can also handle music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobiles also make it possible to buy music online, for example.
It is enough to visit the relevant pages of the operator (or another provider) via mobile Internet and purchase a song or album.
This service could already be a strong argument for the purchase of a music mobile phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is poor and is usually limited to fast-leathered radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their phones with them all the time.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you can feel the phone in your pocket while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least wired handsfree.
If not, you can use the integrated speaker, which has almost every mobile, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of music phones will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than $3,000.
For three and four thousand crowns, you will already make a very decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you will be limited by the absence of output to ordinary headphones.
The best and technically most equipped phones even with a 3.5 mm jack for ordinary headphones cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy operation.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can control really everyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of the control with a previously common tape recorder or perhaps a turntable is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of an erroneously turned on mobile Internet and subsequently a huge data transfer account.
What kind of device to touch
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the corresponding card, you will fit into two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive can cope with 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach for Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not need to spend more than CZK 1,100.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, you should rather reach for specialized mobiles - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokias and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of operation is closer to a separate MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman phones have the same user interface as self-selling MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to four thousand crowns, but with more memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), MP3 players will take you away from the above brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Possibly
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer almost all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classic ones cheaper.
Maybe he won't be missing for long.
We have written many times on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the CTU, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding up so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and penetration high over 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators like to bet on the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), has often said that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that the classical operator with its own network probably does not have a lot of chances (after all, it would probably be difficult to search for frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought significant price reductions, to which even classical operators had to react.
However, even before the introduction of Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile, similar voices were heard in the UK as in our country.
However, it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we do not have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:Fona in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, they need much less customers than a conventional operator.
They do not carry relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile themselves as low-cost – they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, a bet on a new target group can be quite a good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
“The management guys are choosing Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could catch up with us.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
In the Czech Republic, there is no chance, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokeswoman of the Penta financial group, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor arises.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been hidden for a long time by the group GTS Novera, which would like to take the next step to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunication services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe it's flashing for better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should wait until the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any subject with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the Press Department of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 told Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: “So far we have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further.”
He added: “It’s hard to have a virtual operator on T-Mobile by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a specific deal on the table to be able to think in this short term.”
Vodafone is focusing its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "By dealing with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The actions of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a fall in prices and, therefore, to a fall in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when the operators want something, they can pull by one rope, is also evidenced by the thrust around the creation of U:fona.
Probably the greatest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> went at the time of the creation of U:fona from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the CTU website.
Now, however, it is U:fon that is useful as an argument for why not allow a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been further enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and, above all, on his services."
However, due to this approach of mobile operators, the complete lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is directly striking.
This is not just the position of the Czech Technical University, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the United Kingdom and other developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
But he took a typical stance on the whole issue.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator to lease the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential applicants was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," said Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS in response to our question.
From the representatives of the operators, the statement formulated in this way will not be surprising.
It is more than reasonable for the Office to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
Particularly when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country where virtual operators are usually active, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
But apparently the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices is not one of the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
In fact, shocking in the whole case is the touching consonance of the three mobile operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is entirely self-evident.
As well as the exact same price of gasoline at gas stations, it is certainly only a matter of chance and tough competition.
"The Office found no signs of anti-competitive conduct in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are probably also missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of a dominant position in the market is one of many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets prepared by the Czech Technical University, according to which telecommunications are a single market from the point of view of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment it must necessarily be dominant.
Even if we do not allow this argument, it should be at least a warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that the three mobile operators are acting remarkably similarly.
At the same time, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
In the telecommunications industry, the responsibility of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS gives away from the whole matter.
We have met him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s competences in the field of competition in telecommunications failed to be enforced, although many experts promised to improve the situation.
The <0xC3><0x9A>OHS representatives must know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
That's what happens when no one's looking
At the same time, the operation of some pseudo-virtual operators remains unnoticed, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies issuing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, which are only partially public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Its own mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The prices of these companies usually reach only the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, he will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators forbid such resale.
"If the cases you're talking about happen, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we're dealing with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said in response to our question about the issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such activities will not be carried out to responsible people from mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is opposed to such a procedure.
These companies have significant profits and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows for such speculation, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as ordinary customers of mobile operators.
But that should be at least weird.
In addition, another question opens up for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the CSO has quite strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it may not be satisfied with the explanation of the operators that they have no idea of such a thing and their business conditions prohibit it.
When we are not the most expensive
As the text has already fallen several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable drop in prices for services.
In almost all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - too small, or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was in these moments that regulators intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether by formal measures or informal pressure, they then achieved that the first virtual operator was created and more were packed on it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case like a hot potato.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in competences is more than appropriate in these cases.
But let's not throw flint in the rye.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator is coming to us really soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling it expensive than in the rest of Europe.
