Even rats have feelings.
When a rat or cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals have feelings.
But how could we verify that they feel the same way when they behave like us?
In the online magazine "Edge" for several years published the contributions of well-known scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in its series presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it when we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But as soon as we begin to engage in a different kind and open up questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter into an inconceivable terrain, because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it will do what many other animals do: pretend to be dead, run away, or attack.
Humans behave in a similar way, from which some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe it, though.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to the experience of animals.
This is because circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its share in short-term memory and executive or control functions).
This vast area is much more developed in humans than in other primates, and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity might lie in the language nature of man: because so much of his perception is related to language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness did not matter to language, it would certainly be influenced by language, so that animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something intrinsic and subjective, it cannot be measured or, because of special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, it puts us before great problems.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but in addition there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to study processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in the studies of short-term memory in primates, especially in the example of visualization.
But this approach, which was taken by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses more on neural correlates of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but perhaps they are not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the nonfrontal cortex for the implementation of visualization.
