Debate on bilingualism: immersion in English
In this issue of Education Focused, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss candidates’ attitudes towards bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, an academic in California and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, co-authored the book “Worse Than You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose Schools.”
Effectively reaching out to Hispanic voters is a tricky matter.
Barack Obama's educational agenda only proves it.
Obama’s campaign notes that “Afro-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
To combat such performance differences, Obama’s education agenda advocates, among other things, “transitional bilingual education” for those who are just learning English.
But the question for Barack Obama remains whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is stronger than his interest in reducing performance differences.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, a charter elementary school in the Los Angeles East district.
In the vast majority of cases, the pupils of this school are Hispanics from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are still learning English.
Yet in the 2008 state math tests, an incredible one hundred percent of fourth-grade pupils reached the highest level.
Almost the same astonishing ninety-three percent of fourth-grade pupils reached the highest level in state tests of English language and literature.
This incredible success was achieved by a different method than that preferred by Obama.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, continuous assessment of abilities, and an unexcused approach.
Further, and Obama should note, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s pedagogical approach for those who are just learning English is “full immersion.”
Immersion in English emphasizes the almost privileged use of English in teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who is opposed to bilingual education, told me, "We had a tremendous success with one brand new student from Mexico - after twelve months you would enter a class and not know who it is."
"It works," she said, "for us it works."
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for what other schools with large proportions of Hispanic and English learners should look like?
The school’s results should make the answer to this question self-evident, but the educational agenda of its own party (the National Education Association is a long-standing advocate of bilingual education) and its own consistent support for bilingual education obscure the prediction of Obama’s answer.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the matter by saying that people should stop worrying about “only English” laws.
Instead, “you should make sure your children speak Spanish,” he said.
If Obama really wants to erase performance differences, he should think carefully about the educational patterns that work, rather than ridicule and trivialize them.
Oil falls sharply due to renewed economic concerns
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday amid fears that even the U.S. plan to save financial markets would not need to revive the economy.
Oil futures prices fell in early morning trading on the New York Commodity Exchange by up to 7 percent to $99.80 a barrel.
Since last Monday, prices have fallen by more than $20 per barrel.
In the past two weeks, commodity markets have been shaken by financial unrest on Wall Street and also by two powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After peaking at $145.29 a barrel in July, prices fell to nearly $90 a barrel earlier this month, after which huge uncertainty in the financial markets sprang up.
Anxiety gripped investors again on Monday, even after the U.S. Congressional Presidium announced it had reached an agreement on the biggest bailout in history this weekend.
This report has been overshadowed by fresh concerns that the financial crisis is far from over.
In the latest episode of the progressive dissolution, the government announced that Citigroup would buy a banking arm of Wachovia Corporation.
Meanwhile, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalized the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
Analysts at Barclays Capital said the furious weekend talks that led to the plan to save the economy “appear to be unable to revive market sentiment.”
As the economic situation worsens, demand for commodities, including oil, is expected to decline.
"The outlook for the global stock, interest rates and exchange rates markets has become highly uncertain," Deutsche Bank analysts wrote in a report to investors.
"We believe that commodities will not be able to escape the disease.
From a commodity perspective, our biggest concern is the extent to which the US virus will spread to the whole world, and especially to China.”
The bank’s analysts narrowed their expectations for next year as oil consumption fell due to slower economic growth, and lowered their forecasts for gasoline prices by about 20% for 2009.
