The Pride and Obstacles of Black Lives in a Separate City
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks of the larger Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy and gigantic, lies a quiet city in which the pride and complexity of African-American life comes to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black city to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, enough quava, two good prisons."
Now it is a pilgrimage place.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to Eatonville’s annual Zora! festival to pay homage to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains aloof, though it has made it a stopover for tourists by including it in a Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project of the economic crisis.
It’s still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who “knows so little about us that he doesn’t even know what he’s missing.”
Even today, in the year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open debate on races, many locals remain wary of the views of strangers.
“We pay close attention to how our story is told,” says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the city’s oldest parish.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of black ascension and a community of nearly 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is double the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also an oak shielded example of southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that emerged from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the locals are both proud and protective.
And the worries about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt books full of acronyms such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five passages of the Florida tourist guide turned the city a short distance to Route 17, which leads through the often overlooked center of Florida, into a stage of black history and human drama.
With the splash of the big drum in life and literature, Hurston introduced readers to the store of the first Eatonville mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"Left by the road," she wrote, "is a white brown decorated modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and a playground that Howard Miller always takes care of, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned the widow’s new husband, Dash, and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits an hour-long hotel.”
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
This was obviously not a typical Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
“Zora said it the way it was,” says Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson Girls who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a crispy eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time, when she arrived in the city, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that is still proud to wear decent clothes.
Most residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but many grumbled.
"The Zor people have always loved to see," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair in the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her, along with the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood its significance to the world or its legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography, Wrapped in Rainbows.
Change came in the 1980s.
Representatives of Orange County wanted to stretch a five-lane highway through the city instead of Kennedy Boulevard, a local two-lane main road.
Orlando's scaling has already pushed Interstate 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still getting out of a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the struggle for the mixing of races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At the time, a bunch of white guys, they came and threw oranges and stuff at the people who were sitting on the side," Franklin said.
"We actually had a lady here who was killed by it.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court's request for forced integration, and her decision in Brown's case against the Education Chamber stated that it was "offensive to my race rather than glorifying."
Residents now claim that the desegregation of schools, although positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the local youth.
“Negro kids used to hug — I remember — you hug your teacher in the morning, you hug your teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Elly Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted as long as the teachers and pupils came from the same place, she added.
"You're not hugging your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there's a cultural barrier," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped create space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who like her have risen above prejudices with reckless self-confidence and quotes such as "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker traveled to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to revive her reputation.
Five years later, Hurston’s acclaimed biography by Robert E. Hemenway came to the shelves in bookstores, re-incorporating her into the American canon.
The project with the highway arrived just as Eatonville’s most famous daughter found the lights of the ramps again.
Hurston's former neighbors now considered her a savior.
To show what could happen with its highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and many return to the celebration every January.
After several years, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
"The five streams of the highway have resurrected, you would say, a real civic pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd put it more simply: "Dawn saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped to change the image of the city.
Outsiders like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the church in 1993, began appearing in larger numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
The new one-story library (named, of course, after Hurston) was opened in 2006 on the repainted and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes act as a dead end in summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today, it is 90% black.)
Strangers who come looking for the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Permission for most interviews is required in advance and certain things – such as wall paintings in Eatonville’s oldest church painted by whites and depicting blacks in the fields – are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Jones, a brave, confident teacher who likes deep red, are still afraid that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And even as the Hurston Festival grew, domestic pride also increased.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with problems and so on, but not better, not worse, and just as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
The voice of Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, echoes a sincere love for the community as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or the police, which he says he would use some help.
And even younger ones, such as the 11-year-old twins from Winter Park Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they just pass by, think, 'Well, this town is nothing against the others,'" said Alondra Kenon, recently after church.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a moment, it's a very nice city."
Here in New York we all speak fluently financially
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan had stayed away from newspaper stands and huge TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn’t have realized they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never have guessed that in the glassy beehive of offices above their heads, every day, bankers and investment fund managers monopolizing New York City have had the worst “bad day at the office” since the 1929 crisis.
The messengers are still roaring with metal carts on the sidewalks and transporting muffin bakers to breakfast meetings.
The Hispanics are still moving between the towers and wearing, like human mules, fifty ironed shirts hanging from the swings on their backs.
The office rats are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at the street food stalls, and it’s still not possible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between four and seven in the afternoon.
It didn’t look like a crisis at all until, with all the talk of pessimism, I decided to set up a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I had timed this task to cover the late afternoon session at my local J.P. Morgan Chase branch, there were already about twenty people in the queue.
Not in front of checkout windows to pick up or deposit cash, but in front of a counter where older clients order cheque books, tourists ask about the way to the Macy's Mixed Goods Store, and new customers open accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my “licensed personal banker,” came for the same reason I did.
However, compared to me, they have already collected their savings from smaller banks in places where they came from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania or Staten Island.
They raised money from so-called thrifts (slightly similar to construction savings banks), money associations, and from those types of savings banks whose branches operate in only one state and which claim to care for their customers as a family.
In the past year, 15 such banks have quietly gone bankrupt.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion worth of assets, went into bankruptcy, and as the New Yorkers returned home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion worth of assets, tried to catch a rescue buyer.
The office and shop staff, who stood in front of me and feared another collapse, moved their cash to a bank that is perceived as a safe haven and that does most of the Wall Street bailouts.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned fluently in financial terms over the past week.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket was talking on the phone and expressing herself to Lehman Borthers, that bankrupt bank, and to her depleted chief executive Dick Fulda with such familiarity as if she were chatting about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed, roughly 50-year-old housekeeper of my apartment, changed the subject of our usual conversation—Brad, Angelina, or my food delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she told me, “I now have my savings in money market funds.
I've moved it, I'm not taking any risks."
Muslim graves desecrated after Austria's right-wing break
