"To capture the true character, I photograph the master off-stage." Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no calls, no costumes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, disconnected from the concentration on interpretation - just so I can achieve a relaxed expression of a man or a woman.
On the one hand, an artist.
On the second - a man.
Inseparable, aside from privacy, in those moments away from the audience - then you can see a confidential gesture, the depth of a fleeting glance, or the passionate gesture of hands that are carefree, because they are not going to step on stage.
The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-people" alternates the theatricality of performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer composes a unique flamenco iconography from different backgrounds.
The exhibition, which takes place as part of the Mes de la Fotograf<0xC3><0xAD>a Flamenca program, “reflects the ever-increasing international importance of flamenco,” says the author, and explains that “Flamenco-people” “can be any people, but when you look at the photos, you find that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists able to bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and completely captivate the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, it is not necessary to take photos on stage.
He wears his personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the flamenco giants.
Fascinated by the Cante de las Minas festival, Bauer began a long journey of portraying flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on a record camera in 1997.
They are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble a classic photograph.
The use of different stylistic means runs counter to the classical basis of the film and lends it a contemporary spirit, an idea that, according to Bauer himself, also reflects flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, but which does not cease to surprise and develop."
What draws the audience is not the action of the dance itself, the singing or the play, but the personality and character of the artist.
Finding the moment when we encounter the most essential, the spirit that manifests itself in the way of perception, being and experiencing, that was and is the constant of the work presented during these days in the El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata Gallery.
This selection of nearly seventy photographed artists is shaped by well-known flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco and will soon receive a book edition, which will contain the exhibited portraits.
The passion for portraiture led Bauer two years ago to the idea of repeating the idea at the "Portraits of a Sports Veteran" ("SportARTproject").
Although their concept is different from "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "to take pictures of people, to get to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a moment, whether long or short - this is my passion.
I think in photography, a portrait is the most difficult genre.
A person meets or encounters people, personalities he sometimes does not even know, or gives him only a few minutes to take pictures.
Despite such circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.”
A collection of portraits of the contemporary flamenco artist called "Flamenco-people" is on display at the Galleria El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata in de la Mata 20, parallel to Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16 October.
