Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in their blood will have to install an "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol must install a system in his car that prevents him from starting the car intoxicated or if he does not breathe.
The proposal became known in June of this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme Public Prosecutor's Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last for one year.
Its goal is to bring the driver back behind the wheel, which is why drivers will also have to take a retraining course.
In addition to the National Office for Transport Safety, the General Directorate of Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Technology for Automotive Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of motorists accused of driving intoxicated more than once will get behind the wheel again.
Alcolock should prevent this, as it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe beforehand or if a higher than the permissible concentration of alcohol is recorded.
Its price exceeds 1,000 euros and the culprit would have to pay it.
A study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that in the first year after the introduction of this equipment, the offences were reduced by 65 %.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 people could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behaviour before it results in a criminal offence.
And in order to help its implementation, since the legal regulation can be carried out in the usual way, the necessary adjustment of criminal provisions, however, requires a change of the law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although some industrial vehicles and public service vehicles have already been tested.
Tomorrow, Congress will vote on the PSOE (Spanish Workers' Socialist Party) proposal, which recommends installing the system on school buses, as is the case in France.
