Talking from sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may frighten you, but in reality it is meaningless.
This is a harmless sleep disorder called somniloquie.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure many of you have been told that he spoke in his sleep at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime with high fever), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single reason for her arrival.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, nightmares, enuresis nocturna or sleepwalking, but this may not be the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fevers, stressful or inflamed situations.
In any case, this is a little explored phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or vice versa (screaming, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where it manifests itself with great force, it would be advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if he has any problem that causes him great anxiety and in this way manifests itself.
We have said that this is a harmless disorder, therefore it is not treated only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or permanent stress).
However, we can do this by keeping in mind a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Try not to disturb your child too much before going to bed.
Therefore, find quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who can relax, it is possible to use relaxation techniques that will help them gain a certain inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
When the somniloquie appears, try to remain calm.
Remind yourself that it is harmless to the child and that from what happened, he will remember nothing the next day.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It is useless because he is not conscious and you interrupt his sleep.
Even when he speaks, he sleeps, and so he rests.
Keep in mind that if you feel that you are having a lot of trouble several times in a row, it is advisable to seek advice or find out what causes such anxiety in a child.
If you understand what he says (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to interrogate him and pull information from him.
It will be useless, because when he sleeps, he is not conscious so that he can organize his thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what he is saying, but you do not know what he is dreaming about, and therefore why he is saying it, so be very careful how you interpret the information and what conclusions you come to.
Never tell your child that you can ask him or her about his or her secrets at night.
Not for fun.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
Don't worry, it's nothing wrong, it's just an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
