Interview - The Blood That's Sure Again
Hema-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly delighted because Hema-Québec has become one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after the scandal with contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is widely known, the national blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated with the Immune Deficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the wave of public reluctance, the Canadian Government launched in February 1994 a public inquiry, presided over by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at explaining the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and formulating recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever delayed handing over the report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québec, this role was taken up by the Gélinea Committee.
Following Gélineau's and Krever's report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec, which was to be administered by Québec, and the Canadian Blood Company to supply all provinces and both territories.
“When Hema-Québec started its activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Québec blood system,” recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was depressing.
With our continued efforts to increase the safety of blood products and our continued work in this area over the years, we have regained public trust," he says and proudly adds that by the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Québec population had trusted Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its inception on September 28, 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
“At that time, we saw many human cases of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease,” says the woman, who has led the company since its inception in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread in blood.
We have therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, according to which, when we do not know and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, it is necessary to take exclusionary measures.
In April 1999, we therefore refused blood from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that sticking to the precautionary principle made sense.”
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting the HIV virus appeared on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT), which allow to detect in the donor blood directly the presence of the virus itself, and not the presence of antibodies on which the tests previously used were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing it and without being able to figure it out.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting blood contaminated with HIV.
“In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone becomes infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product to occur.
I believe that today we can receive or prescribe the blood transfusion necessary for healing in complete peace,” said the head of the Hema-Québec leadership.
“The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what kind of germs can appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by stabs of insects.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," Dr. Décary continues, stressing that, in addition to a safe supply, Hema-Québec must also count on sufficient supply.
“The demand is growing as the population ages.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate.”
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people offering blood are not accepted because they are, for example, carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mud fever is raging, they are excluded for one year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, the members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to persuade people to give blood, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
“Life is so unfettered today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” Décary said.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before they are deposited at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, abounds in blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000th cord blood sample into the bank, and we expect to collect over 1,000 of it annually.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants,” says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they don't have access to it," because Hema-Québec doesn't have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all the hospitals in Quebec.
