Opinions - Barrick Gold's Orwellian discourse
In a September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he affirms that the world’s largest gold producer has launched prosecutions of three authors and a poor little publishing house for insulting honor in order to spark a “transparent public debate” and demands six million of them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truthfulness, especially when prosecuted for insulting honor, but the law.
It is not surprising that Garver completely omits this crucial distinction.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to conduct a public debate, to bring to ruin anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome, the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums to be prepared to defend and fight in a highly unbalanced fight against an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of a mining company.
Moreover, the tactic in these unbalanced struggles often consists in ruining the defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that will shut the door on the other side and, moreover, will terrify anyone who dares to engage in this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it had to present its view of the matter to public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate normally lies in the exchange of ideas, not in the stab wounds.
It was therefore not enough for the mining company to open its books, its documentation, and to have a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and the funding of independent scientific teams that could bring light to the whole matter.
Barrick Gold, however, appears to have no confidence in public opinion and slammed petitions and letters in support of the authors of the book Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he could demand a "public debate" and at the same time despise the views of the same public?
In the vice president’s world, this word seems to refer only to the heavily paid lawyers, not to all Canadians; it is a rather narrow concept of the term.
In a democracy, the right to speak is also given to the oppressors.
Barrick Gold does not understand — or does not want to understand — that the public, who supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada, does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of mining society.
The public is prepared to hear Barrick and judge the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not within what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant’s mouth should be shut (as part of their prosecution of the “public debate” the Barrick company, incidentally, has just filed an official appeal to the authors of Noir Canada to re-apply to them to use this.
Apart from Garver’s surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university’s freedom to research and seek the truth that is essential to every democratic society.
In general, it denies the right to cite reliable sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that the world’s wealthy businesses do not like without being subjected to repeated prosecution, who else will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have formed it if it followed the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He's entitled to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s exaggerated lawsuit clearly shows that, despite what it claims, it has no desire to have a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, as it is for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to curb this type of unwarranted prosecution.
Operations to Save Wall Street: Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use $700 billion to curb the financial crisis that has plagued Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it assumes: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of saved public money, new measures to capture the number of houses seized due to non-payment, and also the right to monitor the amount of wages paid to managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative to the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, after the end of the two-day negotiating marathon.
“We have made great progress and reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” said Henry Paulson, a spokesman for the Bush administration.
“Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the current crisis on Wall Street,” he said.
“This is a crucial point: if we don’t do it, the trauma, chaos and disruption of everyday life for Americans will be enormous,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
Over the past hours, negotiations have started at maximum turnarounds out of fear of the effect that another failure would have on investor sentiment.
The time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the U.S. president were invited to the negotiations later, and both expressed rather in favor of the agreement, without neglecting to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama credited the addition of the agreement with some measures, in particular those aimed at allowing owners to maintain their residence, and measures on the wages of state-saved workers.
“When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on television.
His Republican rival John McCain, who was asked by another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough features I've read [show] that it's something we're all going to have to spend and move forward with.
To choose inaction is simply unacceptable,” he said.
The goal of the $700 billion plan is to buy back dubious debts and risky and unsold assets of U.S. financial institutions with taxpayers’ money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis unleashed by a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then shifted to other, more widespread forms of loans (PCAAs) and resulted in the freezing of cash and the breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
The collapse of the first draft of the agreement from last week is on the conscience of Republican MPs.
Since the Democrats have agreed that some of the “toxic” assets of troubled companies will only be guaranteed by the government, but will not buy them, there is a belief that the hopeless situation is set in motion.
In an effort to reconcile conflicting views in Congress, a measure was attached stipulating that the government would be able to introduce new fees that would help it get its deposit back if, as a result of the program, it had to absorb losses for five years.
The new plan envisages a first deposit of $250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion will be added if the president deems it necessary.
An additional $350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will receive shares in the rescued companies, which in case of profit will pay him dividends and which he will be able to sell again when it is over.
The federal government will be able to delay the procedures for the seizure of real estate related to the loans covered by the plan, as well as to set limits on the amount of valuation and compensation paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The plan's founders would like to submit it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet clear whether their plan will have a green one.
Yesterday, both the Republican and the Democratic camps continued to oppose the project.
"It's absolutely clear that Washington can't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But earning money from taxpayers is not a solution.”
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed the "Sceptics Committee", presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred distinguished professors of economics, among them three Nobel Prize winners, wrote to us: We ask Congress not to rush too much and carefully examine which way to go,” he said.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis is a global crisis.
After the end of the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which is on the verge of collapse since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) as a result of the crisis of risky loans for the purchase of real estate in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of Europe’s twenty largest banks and one of Europe’s ten largest insurers.
"We will not lose this money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos.
“In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And that’s what savers and households can appreciate in today’s uncertain times.”
On the other side of the Channel, so far, it seems, the British government has begun the nationalization of another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Brigley, of which more than 41 billion (75,5 billion USD) were loans to buy real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will buy off branches and accounts of clients of the British bank.
Bradford and Brigley will be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalized by the British government since the financial crisis began.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a Socially Engaged Icon
His beauty with azure eyes for a long time represented his trump, according to others, weakness.
Did this American actor come out with a charming smile from narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensibilities, and unfailing talents that belonged to him also kept him away from the power category that breeds true stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died on Friday at the age of 83 at his ranch in Connecticut from lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the hefty years of American cinema.
Less majestic than Brando, to whom he resembled and for a long time was his rival on film, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breakdown of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often gives birth to beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother a Hungarian.
From these European roots, one of the famous faces of the American dream was born.
Without exaggerated ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because it saw this whole country in love with self-made man, a fighter in the Pacific War, wounded in battle, who studied acting in Yale in the early 1950s, then attended the New York Actor's Studio and celebrated triumph in theater, television and soon in film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a car racer who placed second at the 1979 Le Mans 24-hour race and a sexual symbol, despite being a exemplary couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With him also leave the shadowy places of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the excitement of his own show-business, which will forever remain to some extent mysterious.
A decent man, in the most noble sense of the word.
Paul Newman's departure this weekend has made film lovers dizzy, while his big roles rival each other on a black canvas of memories.
After him, he defiles more than half a century of ever-changing American seventh art.
A charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969) resurfaces, a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Roof, a 1958 Tennessee Williams adaptation.
From a less ancient past (1990) we remember his sensitive Mr. Bridge, disturbed at an advanced age by a marriage that did not meet all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, an abused, violent, unforgettable delinquent from Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me (In the Sign of Hate), a role intended for James Dean, taken over after his death, which brought Newman to true prominence in 1956.
A sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting (Podraz), Oscar for best film in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful billiards player in Robert Rossen's amazing The Hustler (1961), Martin Scorsese will play the same character in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, earning him one Oscar out of seven nominations in 1987.
This face wandering through the ages, that was him.
It's him again.
In his career, different eras compete with each other.
Young people know him mainly thanks to the iconic Slap Shot of George Roy Hill (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans met him again in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy by the Coen Brothers.
He ended his career as the godfather of the Irish Mafia in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003.
Unlike several film legends who left the craft fairly soon, Newman remained in the industry for a long time, although he condemned Hollywood with its glamour, pomp and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier saw it, not without humor, as a "living challenge to underplay", believing that in his performances he was pushing too hard on the saw.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the role came as a tray, the profession was not always so tender.
However, the first lovers played less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, losers and despairers, whose decline and rebellion were reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known aspects of his shy sensibility.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, offers a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
In 1984, his son Scott, who had been lost to an overdose, was given the film Harry and Son, a work of shame and sadness.
In a wave of tributes to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade Robert Redford (they played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said sadly, "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of life, these are the main qualities of a deceased actor.
Aside from his legendary career, a great civil rights activist, environmentalist, independent film, opponent of the decline of Hollywood is also leaving.
We were used to seeing his likeness on bottles of wine vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods, which we may have found rather tasteless, although at first it was a gag.
However, the profits from the sale went to the account of his Foundation for Hard Childhood.
Thus, rather than being lulled by fame, Newman was engaged in society until the very last moment.
He left a letter to his five daughters containing these sentences: "Always and to the end your father was grateful to his happy planet.
I was honored to be here.”
And it was an honor for us to be able to follow the life path of such a bright and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, an exemplary citizen.
