The psychology of trumping: why are we spending more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known – and seemingly irrational – behavior have been discovered by researchers in the field of neurology and economics at the University of New York.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to lag behind in an auction like eBay, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
The research, using an experimental auction, tried to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group took part in a live auction, and using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method, the active areas of the brain of the experimental subjects were examined.
In both games, participants could win money, but when playing at the auction, an important element of which is to beat the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex, called striatum, began to work intensively when losing.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to the researchers, the screwing of the price can therefore be explained by an effort to avoid a sharp reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, members of the research team from among economists conducted a financial cross-sectional survey.
Under different conditions, three groups were bidding against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, the members of the next group were promised that if they exit the game winning, they will receive another $ 15 for the reward.
The third group received $ 15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups, therefore, was that one group was highlighted as a win and the other as a loss.
However, members of the group playing "against defeat" were willing to go higher than they were in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
“These results cannot be inferred from any previously existing economic theory.
Until now, they have explained the phenomena observed at auctions by the joys of winning and avoiding risk.
Until neurological imaging methods helped us resolve the contradiction between the two theories by now reaching a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is listed as one of the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are being treated. The reason for this is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, characterized by inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the causative agents of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main ways, depending on the causative agents of the disease: hepatitis A and E by the digestive system (for example, infected with food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travellers should in any case protect themselves by vaccination against the virus A and B, there is no vaccine against the virus type C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of an infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, urge to vomit.
Then, on the skin and whites of the eyes, jaundice is formed, the stool lightens and darkens the urine. Treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year around the world, a million people die from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected people are treated with medication.
Also, hepatitis C can have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, the causative agent of the disease destroys liver cells insidiously, and so the first symptoms appear in many cases only in 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, carrying out regular depyrstation is very important.
In three groups, the disease is much more common than the average: among people who underwent blood transfusions before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
