Intelligent car imitates the flight of a bumblebee
What would perhaps be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitation of detectors of obstacles occurring in the natural world?
For example, with bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at the Japanese CEATEC fair, was inspired by bumblebee engineers from Nissan. It was about how to build a new generation of systems to prevent collisions.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has developed the BR23C type biomimetic robotic control system, a robotic mini-auto that is equipped with the properties of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
“During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of an oval shape, which in fact is very similar to our safety protective packaging,” explained Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of the brand in the field of technology PR and R&D.
An important role is played by folded eyes, which allow bees to see in all directions in an angle of view of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the folded eye, the engineers reached for the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at a distance of up to 2 meters from BR23C in a field of view of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which immediately turns into an operation aimed at preventing a collision.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robotic car begins to imitate the movements of the bee and turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent a collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this shifting manoeuvre takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If it weren’t for this, the robotic car wouldn’t be able to respond quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Lab and the robotic car project.
It must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety protective packaging, within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process should not take longer than a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees during avoidance, only the possibility of rotational movement, acceleration and deceleration was used in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer service life than lithium-ion variants.
According to Andoa, an instinctive, intelligent reaction is important, not the ability to process, much less to store data.
This mechanism must process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
It does not need to store and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it constantly uses only a memory of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memory with gigabyte or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing technology for immediate avoidance, which Nissan estimates could reach mass-produced vehicles within 10 years.
Another possibility of application may be the connection of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding road obstacles, would lead the driver to the specified end goal.
