The $700 billion economic bailout bill, which is to be split into several installments to buy back low-quality bank loans, is already in writing.
Half of the amount will be used in the first round.
After further talks, which ended on Saturday after midnight U.S. Eastern Time, Congressional representatives reached an agreement in a days-long debate on a $700 billion rescue package, Reuters reported.
"We have made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic Speaker of the House of Representatives, who said only a deal remained.
The compromise on the package was also supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Finance Minister Henry Paulson said of the compromise: "The program will work and will be effective, but further steps need to be taken."
The written version of the package was released before the Asian markets opened on Sunday at 8 p.m. Washington time (that is, on Monday at 2 a.m. Central European time), but it did not cause any special rise in the stock market.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will vote on the draft legal standard hearing the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, which is to be set up, followed by the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday evening, after which news of the deal was also welcomed in the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made last night and appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program differs from the Bush administration’s original proposal that the entire sum of $700 billion should be spent on the purchase of low-quality mortgage-backed securities at once.
Now it is possible to spend a maximum of half of 700 billion in the first round, so that 250 billion will be used immediately after the matter as expected by Congress on Monday, and the Ministry of Finance will buy for them securities secured by mortgages that are assessed as of poor quality, then the fate of the remaining 100 billion dollars will depend on the decision of the President.
The program will be supervised by a special corps, of which the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank will also be a member.
Spending the second half of $700 billion will depend on the next Congressional decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply combined tactics: it can simultaneously buy back low-quality loans, mortgages and securities secured by mortgages, or other "poisonous" loans.
The purchase can take place within the framework of auctions and directly, the competent representatives of the ministry said.
The legal norm will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance program in which the Ministry of Finance will provide them with a guarantee for the funds presenting a cause for concern, for which the company will then pay a price corresponding to the amount of the expected damages.
As Henry Paulson said, the bill provides the necessary resources to spend up to $700 billion to meet the urgent demands of the U.S. financial system, whether it is a large-scale purchase of bad funds, their insurance, or the prevention of systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the major monetary institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
Bank bosses who are in trouble and waiting for the help of the state, on the contrary, can count on the government to reduce their severance pay - which is simply called "golden parachute" in the overseas slang.
Their payments will be limited only in certain cases, in addition, these restrictions will depend on the type of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The restriction basically means that if the ministry buys as part of the auction, a tax surcharge will be imposed on the gold parachutes if the fallen bank directors are not sent straight to retirement.
In the case of direct repurchase of low-quality loans, the government will act aggressively to ensure that the money for management is not exaggerated.
It must be added that the existing contracts on gold parachutes will not change, the restriction applies only to new contracts, which is supposed to be another incentive to participate in the program.
“This is the first time in U.S. history that there will be a legal restriction on the remuneration of CEOs,” said Barney Frank, chairman of the House Financial Services Committee.
In addition, the state will have the right to acquire a stake in the banks participating in the program, thereby reducing the risk of taxpayers, because once the economy and the rescued bank stand on its feet, they can make money on this transaction.
In the next five years, the president will have to submit a proposal to Congress setting out how the expected losses from the financial sector can be reimbursed to taxpayers.
Of course, there were also voices of doubt on both sides regarding the plan.
“That’s not what the American people asked us to do, because that’s not what taxpayer dollars will protect,” Darrell Issa, a Republican from California, said in a statement.
His Ohio Democratic colleague Mary Kaptur believes that it was precisely those who were responsible for the Wall Street collapse that were pressing for the adoption of the provision.
Industrial prices continue to rise
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month in August 2008, compared to 12.9 percent in August 2007, the Central Statistical Office reported.
Export sales prices in the industry were 1.1 percent higher than in July 2008, down 3.9 percent year-on-year.
Industrial production prices were 0.7% higher as a cause of changes in domestic and export prices compared to the previous month, up 3.2% year-on-year.
Domestic sales prices in the industry rose only minimally compared to the previous month, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing industries also increased slightly, by 0.1 percent, compared to July.
The biggest price increase was in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8 percent), mainly due to the monthly increase in prices in the bag and saddlery sector by 4.6 percent, and the production of footwear by 2.5 percent, respectively.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical materials and products sector (1.6 percent).
Price reductions occurred in the oil processing sector (1.4 per cent), the production of electrical machinery and appliances (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood-processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices in the field of paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, we measured price increases in the range of 0.2 - 0.9%.
In the production and distribution sector of electricity, gas and water, which has a high weight in domestic sales of the industry, prices increased by 0.3% in August, mainly due to the continuing impact of the officially determined increase in gas prices from 1 July.
In the 12-month comparison of domestic sales in individual sectors of the manufacturing industry, prices increased the most in the professional oil processing sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal-working sector, a 13.2 per cent increase in prices was observed, followed by a 11 per cent increase in prices in the food, beverage and tobacco sectors.
Price reductions occurred in the textile and textile industries (2.5 per cent) and in the electrical machinery and equipment industries (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, the price growth rate ranged from 0.6 percent to 9.1 percent.
In total, prices in the manufacturing industry increased by 10.2% over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sectors exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In terms of division by sector, domestic sales showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7%) in the tangible asset production sectors in August.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3%, in the energy and further processing sectors, prices remained unchanged compared to the previous month.
The largest increase in prices compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in August 2008 in the energy and further processing sectors (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods sectors, we measured a price increase of 6.8 percent, while for tangible assets, prices fell by 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, falling by 3.9 percent in the 12-month comparison.
In one month, our domestic currency weakened against the euro by 1.7 percent, against the dollar by 7.1 percent, against the euro by 7.5 percent and against the dollar by 15.9 percent.
