Mp3 Players Accused of Exposing Hearing to Risk
Listening to loud music for a long time and using portable music devices as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
According to a statement published today by the European Commission, which quotes the opinion of the Committee on Science on Health Risks recently emerged and identified (Csrseri) by the EU in an official report circulated in Brussels.
“From this scientific viewpoint,” we read in the notes, “it follows that 5-10% of those who listen to music using portable musical instruments for at least five years, more than an hour a week and keep the device at high volumes, risk permanent loss of hearing ability.”
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people, who often use portable musical instruments and mobile phones at high acoustic levels, can unwittingly damage their hearing in an irreparable way,” admits Meglena Kuneva.
“From the scientific findings,” the leader continues, “there is a clear risk and there is a need to react quickly.
The most important thing is that we need to encourage consumers and make this information public.
We must continue to re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific finding to make them fully effective and keep up with the new technology.”
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to investigate the problem, given the high use of portable musical instruments and the growing number of young people exposed to noise of this origin.
"Scientists confirm the need to be concerned and now the European Commission, together with other members and parties who have raised the issue, will examine what measures could possibly be put in place to better protect children and young people from exposure to noise caused by portable musical instruments and similar devices."
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that may be caused by overexposure to similar forms of noise.
It is possible to greatly reduce these damages by looking for solutions such as reducing the level and duration of exposure.
In its opinion, the Scientific Committee of the EU states that users of portable musical instruments, if they use loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only five hours a week, will exceed the currently applicable limits corresponding to the maximum permissible noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for a long time risk permanent hearing loss after five years.
This problem should affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be estimated between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
