Farewell to the old Paradiso cinema, the cities cancel the historic halls
Cinematographic historical halls are closing in favor of Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is like a blind, like a face without eyes."
The painting, offered by director Giuseppe Tornator, successfully documents what is happening in the big Italian city centers, as well as in rural towns.
The process of limiting cinemas, the birth of large multi-rooms in the suburbs and the subsequent disappearance of mono-rooms in the central zones of cities is one of the events that seem inevitable and irreversible, but also has all the hallmarks of a real cultural crime.
"It's as if we lost a friend, a friend, with whom we shared a bit of a journey and a lot of emotions," feels the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that won Tornator an Oscar and a grand jury prize in Cannes twenty years ago, and which told the poems of a lifetime.
The values obtained by Anec, the main association of operators, speak clearly: in the last five years, 316 traditional-style cinemas have closed their doors, and the highest bills were paid mainly by the halls in the most important cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 less in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures, Emilia-Romagna came first with a loss of 82 cinema halls, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And the proof that the first responsible for their disappearance is the emergence of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have registered the highest number of new cinema multi-sales: 195 more canvases in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 more in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian procedure has developed irrationally,” says Paolo Protti, president of Anecu, “it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that the existing ones will survive, because when one cinema in the city closes, not all its visitors are willing to move to a multiplex.
Then let's not even talk about the lack of subsidy to the fund for the benefit of the operators: the previous government debt is about 10 million euros.
From a moral and ethical point of view, it is a shame that the government does not respect existing laws.
Between 16 million and 18 million euros per year would be needed to support the sector.”
Interesting is the Bologna case, the first Italian city to worry about closures and decided to find a way out by signing a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas in both historic centers and suburbs.
Among the planned standards are steps of tax relief for operators and benefits for the audience in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the restricted transport zone and will have special prices to stop and in some parking lots.
“I like this initiative,” says Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by introducing other measures.”
However, it is certain that in order to be able to stand up to the great power of the multiplex, traditional halls need to improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a topic that has always been important: the closure of the Super Cinema in Bagheria, instead of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to start the "New Cinema Paradiso", which I have been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and as I walk in front of the already closed Rialto or Quirinal in Nazionale Street, where I shared so much emotion that I didn’t have to look at the blackened dust inscriptions, I turn to the other side.”
